default3default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultComments on the biodiversity offsetting proposalsdefault&#xa0;
defaultChoice on use of offsetting
default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRenewableUK is not against the principle of introducing biodiversity offsetting in England on a voluntary basis. Subject to following the mitigation strategy in Box 2 of the consultation document (i.e. avoidance-mitigation-compensation), we would in principle be supportive of the introduction of a fully permissive approach to offsetting, where developers choose whether to use the proposed offsetting metric to assess the impact of their projects and the means for compensation.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe pilot biodiversity metric
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDifferent types of development will affect
default a given habitat in different ways. For wind energy development, it is important to consider its benefits in terms of climate change mitigation and the reduction in greenhouse gas emissions which are resulting from displacing other, more polluting forms of energy generation. This has long-term positive implications for biodiversity protection. At 
defaultthe same time, the footprint of wind energy projects on the land is much smaller than other development which involves buildings, hence the effects on a given habitat or species will be quite different. 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn some cases, wind energy projects are able to provide a number of biodiversity enhancements on site, as part of site management plans. Additionally, in the vast majority of cases agricultural landuses are able to continue on sites where turbines have been installed, again due to the light footprint of wind energy development. 
defaultOn this basis, the metric needs to be adjusted for different types of development and infrastructure and this 
defaultlevel of 
defaultdetail needs to be included in any proposals for the introduction of biodiversity offsetting. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThresholds on offsetting
default3.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor wind energy projects, the threshold needs to be different than those for housing, for example. Wind energy does not have a large footprint on the land and the way it may affect habitats and species will therefore be different to having more ‘solid’ development like buildings. As commented above, i
defaultt is also important to consider its benefits in terms of climate change mitigation and the reduction in greenhouse gas emissions which are resulting from displacing other, more polluting forms of energy generation. This has long-term positive implications for biodiversity protection
default. 
defaultOn this basis, the metric as well as the thresholds need to be adjusted for different types of development. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCovenants
default3.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRenewableUK recently submitted comments to the Law commission’s conservation covenants consultation
default, which are relevant to the suggestion in Defra’s consultation (see Section 5.8) that covenants may be used to secure biodiversity offsetting
default. 
defaultIn summary, under the current system 
defaultwind energy schemes are often affected by restrictive covenants. 
defaultIn some cases t
defaulthey
default 
defaultend up restricting wind energy development, which may otherwise be acceptable in planning
default 
defaultterms.
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder current legislation, restrictive covenants are in favour of one nearby piece of land, so developers can
default 
defaultsometimes negotiate a release with the landowner who holds the benefit, or obtain title insurance to allow a
default 
defaultscheme to continue. In some cases therefore, commercial factors can persuade landowners that a covenant is
default 
defaultno longer necessary or relevant, thus freeing up land for development. This is particularly the case where
default 
defaultcovenants were entered a long time ago by previous landowners and the surrounding area has become more
default 
defaultbuilt up.
default&#xa0;
default3.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnder the new conservation covenants, the body enforcing them will not stand to gain financially from
default 
defaultreleasing covenants, so large areas of land could more easily be sterilised. Unless “public interest” protections
default 
defaultare built into the new system, this runs contrary to planning policy, at a time 
defaultwhen there is pressure to build
default 
defaultnew homes, and when the majority of the public support renewable energy.
default&#xa0;
default3.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt the moment, restrictive covenants are completely separate from the planning regime. So a site could
default 
defaultreceive planning consent for a turbine for example, but the scheme be prevented by a historical covenant in
default 
defaultfavour of a private landowner. If there is to be a new statutory scheme (and particularly because it will make
default 
defaultit easier to sterilise large areas of land and harder to negotiate a release), it is our view that public interest in
default 
defaultland being available for renewable energy schemes should be considered and included
default in any new provisions for the establishment of covenants in relation to biodiversity offsetting
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAny new proposals to introduce covenants for the purposes of biodiversity offsetting should ensure that wind energy is not unduly restricted by covenants which are out of date. 
defaultIt is our view that there are two possible ways of building a “public interest” element into the new system
default, which could solve this issue
default:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultEffects on planning applications
default3.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is our view that, should it be introduced, biodiversity offsetting should not be backdated. Introducing such a requirement and backdating it would have a negative impact on the financial viability of projects which are already in the system. Not backdating any biodiversity offsetting requirements would ensure that wind energy projects which are already in the planning system are not affected. At the same time, new projects which are entering the system will have a chance to consider their options pre-application and choose the best route forward in selecting the suitable sites for proposing development. 
default&#xa0;
